05817nam a22010095i 9780520974579DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20202020cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2019040148  a97805209745797 a10.1525/97805209745792doi  a(DE-B1597)551363  a(OCoLC)1157302803  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aHD8730.5b.V64 2020 4aHD8730.5 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a305.868/85051952231 aVogel, Erica, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMigrant Conversions :bTransforming Connections between Peru and South Korea /cErica Vogel. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (188 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGlobal Korea ;v300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Constructing "The End" -- t1. Peru, South Korea, Peru . . . -- t2. Monetary Conversion -- t3. Religious Conversion -- t4. Cosmopolitan Conversion -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aA free open access ebook is available upon publication. Learn more at www.luminosoa.org. Peruvian migrant workers began arriving in South Korea in large numbers in the mid 1990s, eventually becoming one of the largest groups of non-Asians in the country. Migrant Conversions shows how despite facing unstable income and legal exclusion, migrants come to see Korea as an ideal destination. Some even see it as part of their divine destiny. Faced with looming departures, Peruvians develop cosmopolitan plans to transform themselves from economic migrants into pastors, lovers, and leaders. Set against the backdrop of 2008's global financial crisis, Vogel explores the intersections of three types of conversions- money, religious beliefs and cosmopolitan plans-to argue that conversions are how migrants negotiate the meaning of their lives in a constantly changing transnational context. At the convergence of cosmopolitan projects spearheaded by the state, churches, and other migrants, Peruvians change the value and meaning of their migrations. Yet, in attempting to make themselves at home in the world and give their families more opportunities, they also create potential losses. As Peruvians help carve out social spaces, they create complex and uneven connections between Peru and Korea that challenge a global hierarchy of nations and migrants. Exploring how migrants, churches and nations change through processes of conversion reveals how globalization continues to impact people's lives and ideas about their futures and pasts long after they have stopped moving, or that particular global moment has come to an end.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aForeign workers, PeruvianzKorea (South)xSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aasia.  aclergy.  aconversion.  acosmopolitan.  adiaspora.  aeconomics.  aethnicity.  aethnography.  afinances.  aforeign workers.  aglobalization.  agovernment.  aimmigration.  alabor.  alatin america.  alaw.  amigrant workers.  amigration.  amoney.  anonfiction.  aperu.  apolitics.  apoverty.  arace.  areligion.  areligious clergy.  asocial justice.  asouth america.  asouth korea.  awealth.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package: